{
  "texts": [
    "However, these methods remain inapplicable when pretraining large models, as peak device memory is primarily determined by the activations stored on GPU (when the batch size is large) (Anonymous, 2024b; Muhamed et al., 2024).",
    "Essentially, compared to GaLore, our approach may be viewed as a change in the order of operations, applying the compression one step before GaLore does: when storing activations in memory for the backward pass, rather than to the gradients when updating the optimizer state.",
    "As a result, CompAct satisfies their convergence theorem, which explains how it achieves comparable performance despite the drastic memory savings.",
    "Various works aim at reducing the memory cost of activations in deep learning in general.",
    "(Yang et al., 2024) is a complementary work focusing on saving activation memory generated by nonlinear functions and normalization layers, whereas our work focuses on the activations generated by linear layers."
  ]
}